{"continue":{"rvcontinue":"20181011190500|863590518","continue":"||"},"warnings":{"main":{"*":"Subscribe to the mediawiki-api-announce mailing list at <https://lists.wikimedia.org/mailman/listinfo/mediawiki-api-announce> for notice of API deprecations and breaking changes. Use [[Special:ApiFeatureUsage]] to see usage of deprecated features by your application."},"revisions":{"*":"Because \"rvslots\" was not specified, a legacy format has been used for the output. This format is deprecated, and in the future the new format will always be used."}},"query":{"normalized":[{"from":"Markwayne_Mullin","to":"Markwayne Mullin"}],"pages":{"37205890":{"pageid":37205890,"ns":0,"title":"Markwayne Mullin","revisions":[{"timestamp":"2018-10-11T19:05:32Z","contentformat":"text/x-wiki","contentmodel":"wikitext","*":"{{Infobox officeholder\n|name        = Markwayne Mullin\n|image       = Markwayne Mullin official photo.jpg\n|state       = [[Oklahoma]]\n|district    = {{ushr|OK|2|2nd}}\n|term_start  = January 3, 2013\n|term_end    =\n|predecessor = [[Dan Boren]]\n|successor   =\n|birth_date  = {{birth date and age|1977|07|26}}\n|birth_place = [[Tulsa, Oklahoma]], U.S.\n|death_date  =\n|death_place =\n|party       = [[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]]\n|spouse      = Christie Mullin\n|education   = [[Missouri Valley College]]<br>[[Oklahoma State University Institute of Technology]]\n|website     = {{url|mullin.house.gov|House website}}\n}}\n'''Markwayne Mullin''' (born July 26, 1977) is an American politician, businessman, and former professional [[mixed martial arts]] fighter who has been the [[United States House of Representatives|United States representative]] for [[Oklahoma's 2nd congressional district]] since 2013. He owns several businesses, which he took over at twenty, when his father became ill. Mullin, a member of the [[Republican Party (United States)|Republican Party]], was elected to the U.S. House of Representatives in the [[United States House of Representatives elections in Oklahoma, 2012|2012 elections]], succeeding [[Democratic Party (US)|Democratic]] representative [[Dan Boren]].\n\n==Early life and education==\nMullin was born on July 26, 1977 in [[Tulsa, Oklahoma]].<ref name=rollcall/> He graduated from [[Stilwell High School]] in [[Stilwell, Oklahoma]].<ref name=newsok>{{cite web |url=http://blog.newsok.com/politics/2012/10/11/markwayne-mullin-tapped-to-give-national-republican-address/ |title=Markwayne Mullin Tapped to Give National Republican Address &#124; .Politics |publisher=Blog.newsok.com |date=2012-10-16 |accessdate=2012-11-08 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://archive.is/20121216104445/http://blog.newsok.com/politics/2012/10/11/markwayne-mullin-tapped-to-give-national-republican-address/ |archivedate=2012-12-16 |df= }}</ref> He attended [[Missouri Valley College]] in 1996, but did not graduate.<ref name=rollcall/>  Mullin received an [[Associate in Applied Science|associate in applied sciences]] degree in construction technology from [[Oklahoma State University Institute of Technology]], in 2010.<ref name=rollcall/><ref>[http://bioguide.congress.gov/scripts/biodisplay.pl?index=M001190 MULLIN, Markwayne, (1977 - )] Biographical Directory of the United States Congress. 1774-Present. Retrieved April 13, 2017</ref>\n\n==Business career==\nMullin took over his family's business, Mullin Plumbing, at the age of twenty, when his father fell ill. He also owns Mullin Properties, Mullin Farms and Mullin Services.<ref>{{cite news | url=http://www.kjrh.com/dpp/news/local_news/markwayne-mullin-wins-district-2-congressional-seat | title=Markwayne Mullin wins District 2 Congressional seat | work=KJRH 2 | date=November 7, 2012 | accessdate=November 8, 2012 | publisher=Scripps TV Station Group | deadurl=yes | archiveurl=https://archive.is/20130127212939/http://www.kjrh.com/dpp/news/local_news/markwayne-mullin-wins-district-2-congressional-seat | archivedate=January 27, 2013 | df= }}</ref>\n\nHe hosted ''House Talk'', a [[home improvement]] radio program, on Tulsa station [[KFAQ]] and syndicated across Oklahoma.<ref name=rollcall>{{cite web|author=November 7, 2012 |url=http://www.rollcall.com/new-members/markwayne-mullin-house-r-okla-2.html |title=Markwayne Mullin |publisher=Roll Call |date=1977-07-26 |accessdate=2012-11-08}}</ref><ref name=\"about\">{{cite web|url=http://www.mullinforcongress.com/about-mullin|title=Meet the Mullin Family|publisher=Markwayne Mullin for Congress|accessdate=August 9, 2013|deadurl=yes|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130614090725/http://www.mullinforcongress.com/about-mullin/|archivedate=June 14, 2013|df=}}</ref>\n\n==U.S. House of Representatives==\n\n===2012 election===\n{{See also|United States House of Representatives elections in Oklahoma, 2012}}\nIncumbent [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic]] U.S. congressman [[Dan Boren]] decided to retire in 2012.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.krmg.com/news/news/local/markwayne-mullin-makes-congressional-bid-official/nDfR2/ |title=Markwayne Mullin makes Congressional bid official |publisher=www.krmg.com |date= |accessdate=2012-11-08}}</ref> Mullin declared his candidacy for the [[United States House of Representatives elections in Oklahoma, 2012|2012 elections]] to the [[United States House of Representatives]] to represent [[Oklahoma's 2nd congressional district]] in September 2011. In the six-candidate Republican primary, Mullin ranked first with 42% of the vote, failing to reach the over 50% threshold. State representative [[George Faught]] ranked second with 22% of the vote.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ourcampaigns.com/RaceDetail.html?RaceID=735568 |title=OK District 2 \u2013 R Primary Race \u2013 Jun 26, 2012 |publisher=Our Campaigns |date= |accessdate=2013-08-30}}</ref> In the run-off primary election, Mullin defeated Faught 57%\u201343%.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ourcampaigns.com/RaceDetail.html?RaceID=771199 |title=OK District 2 \u2013 R Runoff Race \u2013 Aug 28, 2012 |publisher=Our Campaigns |date= |accessdate=2013-08-30}}</ref><ref>[http://www.ok.gov/elections/support/ok_results_seb.html State Election Results, Runoff], [http://www.ok.gov/elections Oklahoma State Elections Board].</ref> He branded himself as an outsider; his campaign slogan was \"A rancher. A businessman. Not a politician!\"<ref>[https://web.archive.org/web/20111211151101/http://www.mullinforcongress.com:80/about-mullin/ Archive] of Mullin's campaign site from 2012</ref>\n\nThe second has historically been a classic [[Yellow Dog Democrat|\"Yellow Dog\" Democratic]] district.  However, it has steadily trended Republican, as [[Tulsa]]'s suburbs have spilled into the northern portion of the district. For these reasons, Mullin was thought to have a good chance of winning the election. In the general election, Mullin defeated the Democratic candidate, Rob Wallace, a former [[District Attorney|district attorney]], 57%\u201338%.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ourcampaigns.com/RaceDetail.html?RaceID=705055 |title=OK \u2013 District 02 Race \u2013 Nov 06, 2012 |publisher=Our Campaigns |date= |accessdate=2013-08-30}}</ref> He became the first Republican to represent the district, since [[Tom Coburn]] in 2001,<ref name=\"tulsa\">{{cite news | url=http://www.tulsaworld.com/news/article.aspx?subjectid=262&articleid=20121107_16_EC3_CUTLIN289219 | title=Republican Markwayne Mullin voted into 2nd District Seat | work=Tulsa World | date=November 7, 2012 | accessdate=November 8, 2012 | author=Krehbiel, Mark}}</ref> and only the second since 1921.\n\n===Miami Tribe revocation===\n\nOn February 5, 2014, Mullin introduced the bill [[To revoke the charter of incorporation of the Miami Tribe of Oklahoma at the request of that tribe (H.R. 4002; 113th Congress)]], which would accept the request of the [[Miami Tribe of Oklahoma]] to revoke the charter of incorporation issued to that tribe and ratified by its members on June 1, 1940.<ref name=4002sum>{{cite web|title=H.R. 4002 \u2013 Summary|url=https://beta.congress.gov/bill/113th-congress/house-bill/4002|publisher=United States Congress|accessdate=23 June 2014}}</ref>\n\n===2017 town hall comments===\nIn April 2017, Mullin drew criticism when he was recorded during a town hall meeting telling his constituents that it was \"bullcrap\" that taxpayers pay his salary. He said, \"I pay for myself. I paid enough taxes before I got here and continue to through my company to pay my own salary. This is a service. No one here pays me to go.\"<ref name=HillSalary>{{cite news |title=GOP rep: 'Bullcrap' to say taxpayers pay my salary|url=http://thehill.com/blogs/blog-briefing-room/news/328615-gop-rep-bullcrap-to-say-taxpayers-pay-my-salary-i-pay-for|work=The Hill|date=13 April 2017|accessdate=13 April 2017|author=NIKITA VLADIMIROV}}</ref> According to the January 2012 [[Congressional Research Service]], the [[United States House of Representatives#Salary and benefits|salary of a U.S. representative]] is $174,000 per year, and [[United States House of Representatives#Salary and benefits|benefits]] include allowances, cost-of-living adjustments, enrollment in a pension, health benefits, personnel, mail and office expenses, and a travel allowance.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://library.clerk.house.gov/reference-files/112_20120104_Salary.pdf|title=Congressional Salaries and Allowances|last=Brudnick|first=Ida A.|date=January 4, 2012|website=|access-date=April 14, 2017}}</ref>\n\n===Running for a fourth term===\nDuring the 2012 campaign, Mullin promised to serve for only three terms (six years), meaning that he would have left Congress in 2019.  However, in July 2017, Mullin released an eleven-minute video announcing that he would indeed run for a fourth term in 2018, saying he was ill-advised when he made the promise to only serve three terms.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Krehbiel|first1=Randy|title=Markwayne Mullin to seek fourth term, explains why he's breaking three-term campaign pledge|url=http://www.tulsaworld.com/news/elections/markwayne-mullin-to-seek-fourth-term-explains-why-he-s/article_4d86dc23-965d-57be-b8c2-4d1832371d71.html|website=Tulsa World|publisher=Tulsa World|accessdate=2017-07-13}}</ref>\n\n===Committee assignments===\n* '''[[United States House Committee on Natural Resources|Committee on Natural Resources]]'''\n** [[United States House Natural Resources Subcommittee on Indian and Alaska Native Affairs|Subcommittee on Indian and Alaska Native Affairs]]\n** [[United States House Natural Resources Subcommittee on Water and Power|Subcommittee on Water and Power]]\n* '''[[United States House Committee on Transportation and Infrastructure|Committee on Transportation and Infrastructure]]'''\n** [[United States House Transportation Subcommittee on Economic Development, Public Buildings and Emergency Management|Subcommittee on Economic Development, Public Buildings and Emergency Management]]\n** [[United States House Transportation Subcommittee on Highways and Transit|Subcommittee on Highways and Transit]]\n** [[United States House Transportation Subcommittee on Water Resources and Environment|Subcommittee on Water Resources and Environment]]\n\n===Caucus memberships===\n* '''[[Republican Study Committee]]'''<ref>{{cite web|title=Member List|author=|url=https://rsc-walker.house.gov/|format=|publisher=Republican Study Committee|date=|accessdate=2 January 2018}}</ref>\n* [[Congressional Western Caucus]]<ref>{{cite web|title=Members|author=|url=https://westerncaucus.house.gov/about/membership.htm|format=|publisher=Congressional Western Caucus|date=|accessdate=25 June 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Mixed martial arts record==\n{{MMArecordbox\n| draws=\n| nc=\n| ko-wins= 1\n| ko-losses=\n| sub-wins= 2\n| sub-losses=\n| dec-wins=\n| dec-losses=\n| dq-wins=\n| dq-losses=\n| other-wins=\n| other-losses=\n}}\n{{MMA record start}}\n|-\n| {{yes2}}Win\n| align=center| 3\u20130\n| Clinton Bonds\n| TKO (punches)\n| XFL\n| {{dts|2007|April|7}}\n| align=center| 2\n| align=center| 1:27\n| Tulsa, Oklahoma, United States\n|\n|-\n| {{yes2}}Win\n| align=center| 2\u20130\n| Clinton Bonds\n| Submission (armbar)\n| XFL Superbrawl\n| {{dts|2007|February|3}}\n| align=center| 2\n| align=center| n/a\n| Tulsa, Oklahoma, United States\n|\n|-\n| {{yes2}}Win\n| align=center| 1\u20130\n| Bobby Kelley\n| Submission (rear-naked choke)\n| XFL\n| {{dts|2006|November|11}}\n| align=center| 1\n| align=center| 0:46\n| Miami, Oklahoma, United States\n|\n{{end}}\n\n==Personal life==\nHe and his wife, Christie, live in [[Westville, Oklahoma|Westville]], a few miles from the [[Arkansas]] border, and have five children.<ref name=rollcall/><ref>{{cite news|author=Margot Peppers |url=http://www.dailymail.co.uk/femail/article-2406891/Oklahoma-congressman-Markwayne-Mullin-wife-reunite-twins-separated-birth-adopting-them.html |title=Oklahoma congressman Markwayne Mullin and his wife reunite twins separated at birth by adopting them &#124; Mail Online |publisher=Dailymail.co.uk |date= August 30, 2013|accessdate=2013-08-30 |location=London}}</ref>  He is an enrolled member of the [[Cherokee Nation]], and is one of two [[Indigenous peoples of the Americas|Native Americans]] in the 115th Congress. The other Native American is fellow Oklahoma Republican [[Tom Cole]], a member of the [[Chickasaw Nation]].<ref>{{cite web|author=Aura Bogado on March 1, 2013 \u2013 12:11 PM ET |url=http://www.thenation.com/blog/173145/why-does-congresss-only-cherokee-member-keep-voting-against-vawa# |title=Why Does Congress's Only Cherokee Member Keep Voting Against VAWA? |publisher=The Nation |date=2013-03-01 |accessdate=2013-08-30}}</ref>\n\nMullin is a former professional [[mixed martial arts]] fighter and is listed in the [[Sherdog]] Fight Finder with a 3-0 professional record.<ref>{{cite news|author=Josh Gross |url=https://www.theguardian.com/sport/blog/2016/may/02/ufc-muhammad-ali-act-mma-conor-mcgregor-dispute |title=How the Ali Act could upset the power balance between UFC and its stars\" The Guardian|publisher=guardian.co.uk |date= May 2, 2016|accessdate=2016-05-02 |location=London}}</ref>\n\n[[Joe Kennedy III]] stated on [[Jimmy Kimmel Live!|Jimmy Kimmel Live]] that Mullin was his best Republican friend.\n\n==See also==\n* [[List of Native Americans in the United States Congress]]\n* [[List of Native American politicians|List of Native American Politicians]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://mullin.house.gov/ Congressman Markwayne Mullin] official U.S. House site\n* [http://www.mullinforcongress.com/ Markwayne Mullin for Congress]\n* {{Dmoz|Regional/North_America/United_States/Oklahoma/Government/Federal/US_House_of_Representatives/Markwayne_Mullin_%5BR-2%5D}}\n* {{C-SPAN|markwaynemullin}}\n* [http://www.sherdog.com/fighter/Mark-Mullen-22106/ Professional mixed martial arts record] on [[Sherdog]].com\n* {{CongLinks | congbio=M001190 | votesmart=135898 | fec=C00498345 | congress=markwayne-mullin/2156 }}\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-par|us-hs}}\n{{USRepSuccessionBox\n| state    = Oklahoma\n| district = 2\n| before   = [[Dan Boren]]\n| years    = 2013\u2013present\n| after    = Incumbent}}\n{{s-prec|usa}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Luke Messer]]<br />R-[[Indiana]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=''[[List of current members of the United States House of Representatives by seniority|United States Representatives by seniority]]''|years=282nd}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Beto O'Rourke]]<br />D-[[Texas]]}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{OK-FedRep}}\n{{USHouseCurrent}}\n{{OKRepresentatives}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Mullin, Markwayne}}\n[[Category:1977 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:American Pentecostals]]\n[[Category:American plumbers]]\n[[Category:Ranchers from Oklahoma]]\n[[Category:American talk radio hosts]]\n[[Category:Businesspeople from Tulsa, Oklahoma]]\n[[Category:Cherokee people]]\n[[Category:Members of the United States House of Representatives from Oklahoma]]\n[[Category:Missouri Valley College alumni]]\n[[Category:Mixed martial artists from Oklahoma]]\n[[Category:Native 